  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "YES vote with refinement on delivery timing",
    "content": "Vote: YES — move \"What to Report\" to a standalone file.\n\nReasoning: The bias concern is well-founded and directly relevant to the profile's own Tier 1 requirement (\"No prior exposure... You must encounter the collection cold\"). Knowing in advance that you will be asked \"What happened to your experience across the three examples?\" for Essay 3 is a form of priming that contaminates the naive reading. The critical experiential checks (lines 90-95) are explicitly designed to be non-leading — but they cannot be non-leading if the reader has already internalized them before reading.\n\nThe separation is clean:\n- **Profile.md** (spawn prompt): Role, personality, reading instructions, the general instruction to \"mark it when you notice something happening\" (line 63). This is enough to orient the reader without biasing them.\n- **Reporting-Protocol.md** (delivered post-reading): The specific per-stage questions, final prompts, and critical experiential checks. Delivered after the Preface (for Preface questions), after each essay (for per-essay questions), and after full completion (for collection-level questions and critical checks).\n\nOne refinement: the \"After the Preface\" questions (lines 67-70) are safe to deliver immediately after the Preface since they ask about the Preface itself, not about what's coming. But the per-essay template, collection-level questions, and especially the critical experiential checks should be withheld until the appropriate moment. The standalone file could note the delivery timing for each section.\n\nThe general \"What to Report\" header and the instruction that they will be asked to report could remain in the Profile as a one-liner (e.g., \"After reading each piece, you will be asked about your experience\"), so the reader knows reporting is expected without knowing the specific questions."
  }
}
